Suppose $a$, $b$ and $c$ are integers such that the greatest common divisor of $x^2+ax+b$ and $x^2+bx+c$ is $x+1$ (in the set of polynomials in $x$ with integer coefficients), and the least common multiple of $x^2+ax+b$ and $x^2+bx+c$ is $x^3-4x^2+x+6$.  Find $a+b+c$.

Answer A:
 Solution:
The greatest common divisor (GCD) and least common multiple (LCM) of two polynomials have the following relationships:

\begin{align*}
\text{GCD}(P(x), Q(x)) \cdot \text{LCM}(P(x), Q(x)) &= P(x) \cdot Q(x).
\end{align*}

Given that the GCD of $x^2+ax+b$ and $x^2+bx+c$ is $x+1$, we have

\begin{align*}
(x+1) \cdot \text{LCM}(x^2+ax+b, x^2+bx+c) &= (x^2+ax+b)(x^2+bx+c).
\end{align*}

We are also given that the LCM of $x^2+ax+b$ and $x^2+bx+c$ is $x^3-4x^2+x+6$. Substituting this into the above equation, we get

\begin{align*}
(x+1)(x^3-4x^2+x+6) &= (x^2+ax+b)(x^2+bx+c).
\end{align*}

Expanding both sides, we have

\begin{align*}
x^4-3x^3-3x^2+7x+6 &= x^4+(a+b)x^3+(ab+c)x^2+(ac+b)x+bc.
\end{align*}

By comparing coefficients, we obtain the following system of equations:

\begin{align*}
a+b &= -3, \\
ab+c &= -3, \\
ac+b &= 7, \\
bc &= 6.
\end{align*}

Since $a$, $b$, and $c$ are integers, we can solve this system of equations.

We see that $a=2$ and $b=1$ satisfy the first equation. Substituting these values into the third equation, we get

\begin{align*}
2c+1 &= 7 \\
\Rightarrow\qquad c &= 3.
\end{align*}

Thus, $a=2$, $b=1$, and $c=3$. Therefore, $a+b+c=2+1+3=\boxed{6}$.

Final Answer: The final answer is 6. I hope it is correct.

